15 - Autoboxing and Unboxing in Java

1. What is Autoboxing?
Autoboxing is the automatic conversion of a primitive value into its corresponding wrapper object.
Example: int -> Integer

2. What is Unboxing?
Unboxing is the automatic conversion of a wrapper object back into its primitive type.
Example: Integer -> int

3. Why is it Useful?
It helps when working with collections and APIs that require objects instead of primitives.

4. Example Program
import java.util.ArrayList;

public class AutoBoxingExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ArrayList<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>();

        numbers.add(10);   // autoboxing
        numbers.add(20);

        int first = numbers.get(0); // unboxing
        System.out.println(first);  // 10
    }
}

5. Another Example
Integer num = 50;   // autoboxing
int x = num;        // unboxing

6. Summary
Autoboxing and unboxing make Java code cleaner by allowing automatic conversion between primitive types and wrapper classes.
